There are four key elements involved in digital night vision: Sensors, displays, optics, and image processing.
Work will continue to advance the development and maturity of each of these four elements while addressing the
integration aspects of these areas into a digital night vision system. By combining the maturation of the optics
with the maturation of the display, prototypes will be tested like a night vision goggle. Additionally, HSE will
seek innovative solutions for integrated display/optic packages utilizing different combinations of micro-display
and optical element technologies. Technology gaps to be addressed are: Weight/CG: Control weight and
CG for integrated display/optic; Color: Full Color maintaining daylight readability and night utility; Resolution:
Allows full performance night vision imagery; and Field of View: Greater than or equal to 40 degrees horizontal
and 30 degrees vertical while meeting the following basic performance elements: Electro-Optical Effects: No
noticeable distortion or jitter or other electro-optical effects; Daylight Readability: Readable symbology in full
daylight environment; and Night Utilization: Useable at levels that allow operation in overcast starlight without
significantly reducing pilot night adaptation and without impacting the pilot's ability to see outside of the aircraft.

A Human Systems Integration core/cadre and a Usability Assessment tool for maturing Human Interfaces will be
advanced to address Air Wing of the Future (AWOTF). These capabilities will optimize work/crew station design
to maximize cognitive performance/decision making to support integrated manned and unmanned teaming
(MUM-T) missions for the Air Wing of the Future. Engagement with developing systems like CCA and FVL will
start earlier in the development of systems to advocate for Human Systems Integration in future Naval Systems.
Research will address human performance as a function of cognitive workload and decision support to optimize
situational awareness / decision making to deliver integrated warfighting capabilities.

Transition and continue spiral improvements to an aircraft/aircrew-mounted laser event recorder (LER) to detect
and alert the warfighter when targeted/irradiated by a laser. The LER will record characteristics of the laser
strike (e.g., wavelength, power, pulse duration, etc.), as well as capture a picture of the scene with the global
positioning system (GPS) coordinates. This capability will define the current, and if applicable the changing
vision threat, and will inform future vision protection, addressing evolving threats at greater speed. With
changing threats, dielectric coatings will continue to be refined and evaluated to provide higher optical densities
in the long wavelength visible and near infrared portion of the electromagnetic spectrum. This includes improved
lamination and profiling of dielectric filters. Explore the adding photosensitive filters (i.e., photochromics) to
provide a day /night solution.


