Appropriation/Budget Activity                                                     R-1 Program Element (Number/Name)
1319: Research, Development, Test & Evaluation, Navy / BA 5: System               PE 0605450M / Joint Air-to-ground Missile (JAGM)
Development & Demonstration (SDD)
 The Precision Attack Strike Munition provides a longer-range, precision strike weapon capable of deterring and engaging maritime and land-based targets. PASM
 builds off of the subsystem maturation, integration, and demonstration efforts of the LRAM JCTD. PASM will provide asymmetric advantages in range, stand-off and
 lethality. PASM is designed with a Weapons Open System Architecture (WOSA) to form fit multiple types of payloads based on mission while using common mounting
 systems and launchers to simplify logistics requirements. PASM is initially designed to utilize mature, non-integrated capabilities for the fire control system. The AH-1Z
 is the threshold platform for the USMC. The PASM system includes missiles, trainers, containers, federated platform integration solution, support equipment, modular
 payloads, and software modifications.

 The Modular Common Launcher (MCL) is the next generation multi-purpose launcher for USN and USMC Vertical Take Off Landing (VTOL) platforms. The MCL
 enables multiple carriage of the Precision Attack Strike Munition (PASM) on the AH-1Z aircraft. The PASM fills a long-range Precision Guided Munition (PGM) capability
 gap for the AH-1Z. The modular concept enables mixed loadouts and carriage of up to four weapon systems from a single aircraft station that significantly enhances
 mission lethality and flexibility. The MCL provides a platform for future integration of legacy weapons (e.g. Hellfire, JAGM, APKWS and unguided 2.75 in rockets) and
 emerging weapons (e.g. PASM, expanded APKWS and Air Launched Effects) on the AH-1Z, MH-60, and other platforms. The MCL adds capability and flexibility to
 better align loadouts with mission requirements and significantly simplifies sustainment/logistics support. As the MCL is subsequently qualified for carriage of legacy
 stores, it provides a cost-effective and highly supportable way to mitigate readiness issues with LAU series Hydra 70 2.75-inch aircraft rocket launchers and to resolve
 significant obsolescence issues afflicting the M299 HELLFIRE Missile Launcher (HML).

 The FY 2027 cost of the PASM Middle Tier of Acquisition and MCL efforts is $193.512 million, including RDTE and procurement of Prototype units for operational utility
 demonstration. The Department will certify FYDP funding in a future budget submission.

 JUSTIFICATION FOR BUDGET ACTIVITY: This program is funded under system development and demonstration because it includes those projects that have passed
 Milestone B approval and are conducting engineering and manufacturing development tasks aimed at meeting validated requirement prior to full-rate production
 decision.

